  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The software tool \"stineb/rpmodel,\" authored by Benjamin Stocker from ETH Zurich, has garnered a total of 225 downloads since its release in 2019. Despite being tagged in multiple scholarly domains including medicine, engineering, and computer science, the tool currently has no documented citations in academic literature, indicating limited engagement in scholarly discourse.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Launched in 2019, the \"stineb/rpmodel\" software represents a contribution to various interdisciplinary fields, such as engineering and archaeology. The tool remains accessible via Zenodo and has seen a substantial number of downloads, totaling 225, reflecting interest and potential utility among users. However, as of now, it has not been cited in any academic publications, hinting at a need for broader community engagement and visibility within the scholarly community.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of online presence, the software appears to be underutilized as it has not registered any online mentions in prominent platforms, nor does it have associated discussions or endorsements in academic forums. This lack of visibility could impact its adoption and integration into related research, posing challenges for users seeking to apply the tool in practical or academic settings.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The authorship by Benjamin Stocker at ETH Zurich indicates a caliber of research backing, yet the tool's impact may be undermined by limited outreach. The potential for broader application and citations lies in targeted outreach efforts, collaboration with educators for teaching adoption, and enhanced visibility on knowledge-sharing platforms.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">While the software has accrued a modest number of views, totaling 1,151, the gap between views and downloads suggests a need for further promotion to convert interest into actual usage. Striving for future engagement could enhance its role across various domains, from engineering to psychology, and could ultimately increase its citation rate in relevant academic literature.</p>",
